Date: Wed, 6 May 2026 17:07:18 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 07/13] Fix auth.routes.js: real password check, env JWT
 secret, OTP TTL
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The previous implementation had multiple critical bugs:

1. POST /api/auth/login NEVER VALIDATED THE PASSWORD. It only checked
   the OTP. Anyone who knew (or guessed) a 6-digit OTP could log in as
   any user without their password.

2. The JWT was signed with the literal string 'SECRET_KEY' — a hard-
   coded secret that did not match what auth.middleware.js used to
   verify tokens ('imis_secret') or what user.controller.js used
   ('secret123'). Tokens issued by login could not be verified by the
   middleware, so any protected route would 401 immediately after a
   successful login.

3. OTP_STORE was a plain object with no TTL, so issued OTPs lived
   forever (until process restart) and were never cleaned up.

4. send-otp returned the OTP in the response unconditionally, leaking
   it even in production.

5. send-otp didn't verify that the username belongs to a real user, so
   an attacker could enumerate / fill memory with junk OTPs.

This rewrite:
- Validates password with bcrypt.compare() *before* OTP verification.
- Reads JWT_SECRET / JWT_EXPIRES_IN from env (with safe dev defaults).
- Adds 10-minute OTP TTL via Map<username, { otp, expiresAt }>.
- Verifies the user exists before issuing an OTP.
- Returns OTP in the response only when EXPOSE_OTP env var is truthy,
  defaulting to true in dev so the user can log in without configuring
  any SMS/Email service. Set EXPOSE_OTP=false in production.
- Deletes the OTP after a successful login so it can't be replayed.
- Returns a sanitized user object (no password hash) on success.
